summary.seg: This manuscript contains a collection of Philosophical texts in Greek. It is formed of two parts, both copied by the Cretan scribe and printer Zacharias Kallierges (b. before 1473, d. after 1524); they were produced probably around the same time, since the paper shows the same watermark. The two parts, however, are distinguishable by the presence of two distinct sets of signatures numbering the quires, both starting from the number 1.

Part I contains Proclus' Commentaries on Plato's Republic. Zacharias Kallierges copied the text with a close collaborator (their hands alternate within the same page of text), who has been recently supposedly identified as his son Nikolaos (see Katzopoulou (2012)). Kallierges copied this same text in three other manuscripts:
Paris, Bibliothèque Nationale de France, gr. 1831
Paris, Bibliothèque Nationale de France, gr. 1834
Vatican, Biblioteca Apostolica Vaticana, Pal. gr. 63
. Their script, decoration and layout are strikingly similar, and illustrate the scribe's working practices (see Katzopoulou (2012)).

Part II contains two texts, Syrianus' Commentaries on Aristotle's Metaphysics, and an extract on providence from the Questions and Answers, a work traditionally attributed to Alexander of Aphrodisias (on this quaestio see Sharples (1998), p. 390).

The manuscript was donated to Gonville and Caius College by John Caius (1510-1573), the second founder of the College. The English physician travelled in Italy from 1539 to 1544, where he consulted various manuscripts (see S. Berlier, 'John Caius et le De usu partium. Contribution à l'histoire du texte de Galien', in: Revue d'Histoire des Textes n.s. 6 (2011), 1-14 (pp. 5-6)) and it was there that he probably acquired at least some of the Greek manuscripts he later bequeathed to the College.
Gonville and Caius MS 495/264 was used as an exemplar for Cambridge, University Library, Ll.5.4 .

foliation.p: Traces of an older foliation in ink are visible in the upper right corner of the recto of the leaves from f. [200]r (183). This foliation does not correspond to the present one.

supportDesc.condition: The codex is in good condition. There are large brown stains throughout part II of the manuscript, see e.g. f. 109r and on ff. 129r-129v. Worm holes, in particular in the first and last leaves.

binding.p: Western early modern binding. Full leather cover over couched-laminate boards. Blind tooling on both boards. On the spine are pasted two paper labels with the shelfmarks, 264 and 49 (the last number is missing, the shelfmark is 495). Gold tooling on the boards edges. The edges are coloured in green.
binding.condition: The leather is damaged on the edges and where the boards touch the spine.

accMat.p: F. [iii] is a paper stub, on which a slip of paper, from a manuscript in Latin, is pasted (from a 14th c. MS in Italian hand in the opinion of M.R. James, A descriptive catalogue of the Manuscripts in the Library of Gonville and Caius College, vol. 2 (Cambridge: Cambridge University Press, 1908), p. 567).

ff. [i]-[ii], [v]-[vi] are later paper endleaves, with watermark in form of Grapes ( 37 20 ), in the centre of the leaf (no exact parallels in the main repertoires, the motif is common in the 17th-18th c.).

history.acquisition: The manuscript was donated to Gonville and Caius College by John Caius (1510-1573) Caius, John, 1510-1573 . A note on f. [iii] recto attests to the donation: Collegio suo de Goneville | et Caius in Canta | brigia, Joannes Caius | dono dedit. On the left pastedown and in the lower margin of f. 1r are pasted two bookplates, of Gonville and Caius College Library and of Gonville and Caius College.

recordHist.source: Description (2021) draws partly on M.R. James, A descriptive catalogue of the Manuscripts in the Library of Gonville and Caius College, vol. 2 (Cambridge: Cambridge University Press, 1908), p. 567.

availability.p: Visitors to Gonville and Caius College who wish to consult Lower Library material are required to apply to the Library in advance of their visit. For information on eligibility and admission procedures see: Gonville and Caius College: Library Information.

msItem.author: Proclus
msItem.title: Commentaries on Plato's Republic
In Platonis rem publicam commentarii
msItem.rubric: f. 1r Πρόκλου Λυκίου, πλατωνικοῦ διαδόχου περὶ τοῦ τίνα χρὴ καὶ πόσα, πρὸ τῆς συναναγνώσεως τῆς Πολιτείας Πλάτωνος κεφάλαια διαρθρῶσαι, τοὺς ὀρθῶς ἐξηγουμένους αὐτήν.
msItem.incipit: f. 1r Τοὺς προλόγους τῶν Πλατωνικῶν διαλόγων
msItem.explicit: f. [107]r καὶ ὧν ταῦτα αἴτια, μειζόνως αἴτιον ἂν ὑμνοῖτο.
msItem.note: Ed. W. Kroll, Procli Diadochi in Platonis rem publicam commentarii , 1, Leipzig 1899 [repr. Amsterdam 1965], pp. 5-296

The lower part of f. [6]r and f. [6]v have been left blank in order to point out to a common lacuna to the text tradition: οἱ συνόντες ἀλλήλοις δυνατώτερόν ἐστιν τοῦ δεομένου (Kroll 1899, pp. 19 l. 25-20)

support.material:
Western paper, folded in folio. Watermarks: ff. 1-[107] Anchor in a circle surmounted by a six-point star ( 70 42 ) in the centre of the leaf, very similar to Harlfinger Ancre 11 , which is dated in 1504.
f. [iv] Flower with five petals ( ca. 35 ca. 35 ) in the centre of the leaf, comparable to Briquet Fleur 6376 and 6378 , which are dated to 1492, 1494 and 1508 (Venice).

collation.p: Part I is formed mainly by quinions.
collation.signatures: Signatures in red ink, formed by Greek numbers and, below, Αrabic numbers, original to the production of the manuscript, on the first leaf of the quires, under the last line of the text, right, from αον 1 ( f. 1r) to ιβον 12 ( f. 105r).
collation.catchwords: Vertical catchwords, written from the top down, by the scribes, in the lower margin, verso, of the last leaf of the quires, near the gutter.

handNote.p: Hand A: Zacharias Kallierges (b. before 1473, d. after 1524) Kalliergēs, Zacharias, active 1499-1523 (Ζαχαρίας Καλλιέργης, RGK I, 119; on him see also RGK II 156; RGK III, 197). The scribe alternates in the copy with a collaborator (hand B) throughout all this part of the manuscript.
The text is written in a brown ink; titles and initials in red.

Hand B: an anonymous collaborator of Zacharias Kallierges (for the identification see Chatzopoulou (2012), pp. 23-24, esp. n. 84, who thinks he could be his son Nikolaos), who displays a minuscule script similar to Kallierges' hand. Hand B alternates in the copy with Kallierges (hand A) throughout all this part of the manuscript.
The text is written in a brown ink.

decoDesc.decoNote: On f. 1r, over the title, and on f. [107]r, after the end of the text, there are ornamental interlace motifs in red ink. Small rinceaux in red ink are at both sides of the title.
Initials in ekthesis in red ink are decorated with a simple vegetal motif, with rinceaux, see e.g. f. 1r.
Minor initials in red ink with or without small ornamental motifs.

additions.p: On f. [iv] recto there is a note concerning the donation of the manuscript to the College by John Caius (see Acquisiton for transcription). Over the note are pasted two paper labels: the first reports the number of the MS in E. Bernard, Catalogi librorum manuscriptorum Angliae et Hiberniae (Oxford, 1697), 1010, the second the shelfmark, 495.

origin.p: Part I of the manuscript was copied by Zacharias Kallierges and a close collaborator in the first two decades of the 16th c., as the watermarks suggest; Chatzopoulou places the copy in particular around the middle of the first decade of the century (see Chatzopoulou (2012), p. 24).

support.material: Western paper, folded in folio. Watermarks: ff. 109-[226] Anchor in a circle surmounted by a six-point star ( 70 42 ) in the centre of the leaf, very similar to Harlfinger Ancre 11 , which is dated in 1504.

collation.p: Part II is formed by 11 quinions and a quaternion.
collation.signatures: Signatures in red ink, formed by Greek numbers and, below, Αrabic numbers, original to the production of the manuscript, on the first leaf of the quires, under the last line of the text, right, from αον 1 ( f. 109r) to ιβον 12 ( f. 219r).
collation.catchwords: Vertical catchwords, written from the top down, by the scribe, in the lower margin, verso, of the last leaf of the quires, near the gutter.

handNote.p: Hand A: the texts have been copied by Zacharias Kallierges (b. before 1473, d. after 1524) Kalliergēs, Zacharias, active 1499-1523 (Ζαχαρίας Καλλιέργης, RGK I, 119; on him also RGK II 156; RGK III, 197).
The text is written in a brown ink; titles and initials in red.
Hand a: a contemporary hand wrote marginal annotations (mostly corrections) in the margins, in a minuscule informal script (see e.g. ff. [116]v, [200]r).
Hand b: a contemporary or slightly later hand wrote a few marginal annotations in Greek and in Latin (see e.g. ff. [202]r, [210]r).

decoDesc.decoNote: On ff. 109r, 159r and f. [198]v there are friezes in a rope motif in red ink.
Initials in ekthesis in red ink are decorated with a simple vegetal motif, with rinceaux, see e.g. f. 109r.
Minor initials in red ink with or without small ornamental motifs.

On f. 109r, over the title, there is an ornamental motif similar to a flower, in red ink. Small rinceaux in red ink form a sort of frieze on f. [143]v; similar elements are present to the sides of the ending of the text forming a cul-de-lampe on f. [158]v.
Small diagrams in red ink by the scribe, see e.g. f. [130]r.

origin.p: Part II of the manuscript was copied by Zacharias Kallierges in Italy, probably around the same period he copied part II, as the leaves show the same watermark.
